'''Operation Paravane''' was a British air raid of [[World War II]] that inflicted heavy damage on the [[German battleship Tirpitz|German battleship ''Tirpitz'']]. The attack was conducted on 15 September 1944 by 21 [[Royal Air Force]] [[heavy bomber]]s, which flew from an airfield in the north of the [[Soviet Union]]. The battleship was struck by one bomb, and further damaged by several near misses. This damage rendered ''Tirpitz'' unfit for combat, and she could not be repaired as it was no longer practical for the Germans to sail her to a major port.

The attack on 15 September followed a series of raids conducted against ''Tirpitz'' by [[Royal Navy]] aircraft carriers between April and August 1944 that sought to sink or disable the battleship at her anchorage in [[Kåfjorden (Alta)|Kaafjord]] in the far north of Norway, so that she no longer posed a threat to Allied convoys travelling to and from the Soviet Union. While the first of these raids was successful, the other attacks failed due to shortcomings with the [[Fleet Air Arm]]'s strike aircraft and the formidable German defences. As a result, the task of attacking the battleship was transferred to the RAF's [[RAF Bomber Command|Bomber Command]]. [[Avro Lancaster]] bombers from the Command's two elite squadrons flew to their staging airfield in the Soviet Union on the night of 11/12 September, and attacked on 15 September using heavy bombs and air-dropped mines. All of the British aircraft returned to base, though one of the Lancasters later crashed during its flight back to the United Kingdom.

Following Operation Paravane, the German Navy's commander decided to use ''Tirpitz'' as a static artillery battery at the town of [[Tromsø]]. The Allies were unable to confirm the extent of the battleship's damage, and conducted two further heavy bomber raids against her in late 1944. ''Tirpitz'' was sunk with heavy loss of life on 12 November during the second of these attacks.

==Background==
{{see also|List of Allied attacks on the German battleship Tirpitz}}
From early 1942, ''Tirpitz'' posed a significant threat to the [[Arctic convoys of World War II|Allied convoys]] transporting supplies through the [[Norwegian Sea]] to the Soviet Union. Stationed in [[fjord]]s on the Norwegian coast, the battleship was capable of overwhelming the close-escort forces assigned to the Arctic convoys or breaking out into the North Atlantic.{{sfn|Ellis|1999|pp=294–295}} To counter this threat, the Allies needed to keep a powerful force of warships with the British [[Home Fleet]], and [[capital ship]]s accompanied most convoys part of the way to the Soviet Union.{{sfn|Bennett|2012|p=9}}{{sfn|Faulkner|Wilkinson|2012|p=109}}

[[Royal Air Force]] (RAF) heavy bombers conducted a series of unsuccessful raids on ''Tirpitz'' shortly after the battleship arrived in Norway from Germany in January 1942. ''Tirpitz'' was initially based at [[Fættenfjord]] near [[Trondheim]], which lay within range of British bombers flying from Scotland.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=14–16}} The first raid took place on 30 January, and involved nine [[Handley Page Halifax]] and seven [[Short Stirling]] bombers. Due to cloud over the target area, only one of the bombers sighted ''Tirpitz'' and none inflicted any damage. One Halifax crashed into the sea on its way back to Scotland, but its crew were rescued.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=16–17, 170}} The next raid on Fættenfjord took place on 30 March, with the attacking force comprising 33 Halifaxes. However, the operation was again frustrated by heavy clouds over the target area and none of the aircrew sighted ''Tirpitz''. Four of the Halifaxes were shot down, and two others crashed while returning to base.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|p=27}} Another attack was mounted by 30 Halifaxes and 11 [[Avro Lancaster]]s on the night of 27/28 April. While ''Tirpitz'' was located and attacked by the aircraft of the first wave, no damage was inflicted and five heavy bombers were lost.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=31–33, 170}} The final raid in this series took place the next night, and involved 21 Halifaxes and 12 Lancasters. The attackers found ''Tirpitz'' covered in a protective smokescreen, and the battleship again escaped damage; two British aircraft were destroyed.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=33–34, 170}} 
[[File:The Royal Navy during the Second World War A22634.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.2|alt=Black and white photograph of a World War II-era warship in a small bay with a steep and snow-covered shoreline. Clouds of smoke are being blown from the shoreline towards the ship.|A British aerial reconnaissance photograph of ''Tirpitz'' moored at Kaafjord in northern Norway. The artificial smoke generators on the shores of the fjord have not yet obscured her.]]

While plans for further heavy bomber attacks on ''Tirpitz'' were developed throughout 1942, none took place.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|p=43}} One of the options considered during this period was to stage the bombers through a base in the northern Soviet Union, but this was judged impractical as little was known about the suitability of Soviet airfields for heavy bombers at the time.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=46–47}} Two squadrons of [[RAF Coastal Command]] [[Handley Page Hampden]] torpedo bombers operated from [[Severomorsk|Vaenga]] in northern Russia during mid-September 1942 to counter ''Tirpitz'' or any other German warships which attempted to attack Allied convoys, but these aircraft did not make contact with the enemy.{{sfn|Herington|1954|pp=295–297}}

Further plans for air attacks on ''Tirpitz'' were developed during 1943, but none eventuated. During 1942 and 1943 British inventor [[Barnes Wallis]] attempted to develop a version of his "[[bouncing bomb]]" concept for use against ''Tirpitz'' alongside the larger weapons which were successfully used to attack several German dams during [[Operation Chastise]] on 16/17 May 1943.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|p=51}}  [[No. 618 Squadron RAF|No. 618 Squadron]] was formed in April 1943 equipped with [[de Havilland Mosquito]]s to execute this attack, but trials of the "Highball" bouncing bombs during the year were unsuccessful and the plan was abandoned in September.<ref>{{cite web|title=618 Squadron|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/history/618squadron.cfm|website=Historical Structure of the Royal Air Force|publisher=Royal Air Force|accessdate=30 July 2016}}</ref>{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|pp=51–52}} In the meantime, ''Tirpitz'' was transferred to a new base at [[Kåfjorden (Alta)|Kaafjord]] in the far north of Norway in late May 1943.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|p=52}} This anchorage was well protected, with the defences including equipment capable of rapidly generating an artificial smokescreen as well as a large number of anti-aircraft guns located in shore batteries and warships.{{sfn|Tactical, Torpedo and Staff Duties Division (Historical Section)|2012|p=135}} During June 1943 consideration was given to attacking the battleship with [[United States Army Air Forces]] [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]] heavy bombers flying from the United Kingdom and landing in the Soviet Union, before making another attack on their return flight. However, such a mission was judged to be impractical by the RAF as it was expected that German fighter aircraft would heavily attack the bombers and ''Tirpitz'' would be covered by a smokescreen by the time they arrived over the target area.{{sfn|Sweetman|2000|p=53}} The only attack made against ''Tirpitz'' by land-based aircraft prior to September 1944 was a small raid conducted by 15 Soviet bombers on the night of 10/11 February 1944 which did not inflict any damage on the battleship.{{sfn|Bishop|2012|p=295}}

The Royal Navy repeatedly attacked ''Tirpitz'' at Kaafjord from September 1943 until August 1944. On 23 September 1943 the crews of two British midget submarines succeeded in penetrating the defences around the battleship during [[Operation Source]], and placed explosive charges in the water beneath her. This attack caused extensive damage to ''Tirpitz'', putting her out of service for six months.{{sfn|Woodman|2004|p=340}} Further midget submarine attacks were considered infeasible, and an air raid designated [[Operation Tungsten]] was conducted by Royal Navy aircraft carriers as repairs to the battleship neared completion on 3 April 1944. ''Tirpitz'' did not suffer heavy damage in this operation, but was placed out of action for several additional months while repairs were completed.{{sfn|Bennett|2012|pp=14–17}}{{sfn|Garzke|Dulin|1985|p=267}} The Home Fleet sortied to attack Kaafjord on a further four occasions between April and July; all but the last of these operations were frustrated by bad weather, and the [[Operation Mascot]] raid on 17 July did not inflict any damage on ''Tirpitz''.{{sfn|Roskill|1961|pp=156, 170}} Four further carrier attacks targeting ''Tirpitz'' were undertaken between 22 and 29 August during [[Operation Goodwood (naval)|Operation Goodwood]], but again resulted in only minor damage to the battleship.{{sfn|Roskill|1961|pp=159–161}}

==Planning==
{{Location map+ | Russia Northwestern Federal District|relief=1
|caption = The location of Kaafjord in northern Norway and Yagodnik in the Soviet Union
| places =
  {{Location map~ | Russia Northwestern Federal District
    | label = Kaafjord
    | lat_deg = 69.9353
    | lon_deg = 23.0454 }}
  {{Location map~ | Russia Northwestern Federal District
    | label = Yagodnik
    | lat_deg = 64.402778
